  "exemplar_id": "ex_cellulitis_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "45-year-old male with poorly controlled type 2 diabetes (last A1c around 9, no longer self-monitoring) presenting with a one-week history of a swollen, red, painful area around the right ankle that started looking 'strange' yesterday. He has an existing ulcer on the left heel and a scab on the affected right leg that is now an open wound leaking white discharge. He reports feeling hot over the last 12 hours but has no thermometer at home. The doctor has established that the area is red, swollen, painful with movement, and that the patient has reduced sensation in his feet from diabetic neuropathy.",
  "good_next_question": "Is the pain a lot worse than the redness would suggest — like, severe deep pain that feels out of proportion to how the skin looks?",
  "rationale": "This question screens for necrotizing fasciitis, which is the can't-miss diagnosis in any cellulitis presentation and is dramatically more dangerous in a poorly-controlled diabetic with an open wound — exactly this patient's profile. Pain out of proportion to exam findings is the single most sensitive early flag for nec fasc, often preceding the classic late signs (crepitus, bullae, dusky skin, anesthesia over the area). The diabetic neuropathy here makes this question even more urgent, because reduced baseline sensation can mask the deep pain that would otherwise alarm the clinician, and a patient who still reports severe disproportionate pain through neuropathy is a major red flag. Catching this fork early changes disposition completely: nec fasc is a surgical emergency requiring immediate consult and debridement, while uncomplicated cellulitis can be managed with antibiotics and close follow-up. Asking this beats further characterizing the wound discharge or asking about systemic symptoms first because those are nonspecific, while the pain-out-of-proportion question targets the single highest-stakes alternative diagnosis.",
  "tags": [
    "rash",
    "middle_aged",
    "infectious",
    "red_flag_screen",
    "necrotizing_fasciitis",
    "diabetes_complication"
  ],
